December 23\nand the steady selling of the white\nmetal by the Indian government. It is\nalso believed that production has been\ncarried on at too high a rate in view\nof the decreasing demand for silver.\nreport was that certain well-known\nnational politicians had become in\nterested.\nAffairs will reach their climax on\nJanuary 19. when the annual meeting\nof the stockholders is held.\nStrenuous efforts will be made before\nthat, however, to overcome the present\napparent atallmate.\nR. W. Woodruff, president of the White\nMotor 00. of Cleveland, and also of the\nCoca Cola Co. of Atlanta, in New York\nthis week attending the automobile\nshow, says that the problem of pros\nperity or depression rests largely with\nthe way the big corporations handle\nthemselves in the next few months.\nThe size-up of this business leader\nwho, at 39 years of age. heads two of\nthe largest. American businesses \u2014one\nin the South and one in the Middlewest\n\u2014is thus stated:\n\u2018Corporations can put their money\naway in the corporate \u2018soek-end.\u2019 cur\ntail production, reduce labor and can\ncel and withhold commitments, begin\nning again the vicious circle \u2014unem-\nployment, diminished demand, more\ncontraction, more unemployment, and\nthe pessimist will paint the picture of\n1930.\n\"Or. corporations can put their sur\nplus back into circulation by continu\ning and extending their operations\u2014\nspending money to buy equipment and\nnew machinery.\u201d\nMr. Woodruff, himself, is optimistic:\n\"There is no commodity price specula\ntion. inventories are low, hand-to-mouth\nbuying continues and there is ample\nsupply of credit at reasonable rates.\nCorporations are financially stronger\nthan at any time in American history.\u201d\nHe belongs to the forward march\nbrigade of big business.\nL. C. Harbison, president of the\nHousehold Finance Corporation, which\nhas offices in 62 cities in 12 industrial\nStates, and lends sums of $3OO or less\nto individuals at reasonable rates, is\nencouraged over the present business\noutlook.\n(Cearrteht. IMO. by North American New\u00bb-\npaper Alliance*\nTHE EVENING STAR. WASHINGTON. D. C.. WEDNESDAY. JANUARY 8. 1930.\nLast year the world production was\n2.>{>,UOu,ihnj ounces, compared with 248,-\n400.000 ounces in 1928 and 251.200.000\nounces in 1927. Although, meanwhile,\nthere has been an expansion in the\nuse of silver lor the arts, this has not\nat all compensated the effect of the\nsteady forcing of silver into the market\nby China and India, to which may be\nadded the influence on the price of the\ndemonetisation of silver in European\ncountries.\nThe most serious eonsequenc.es of the\nprice decline of silver are those now\ntaking place in China. These Involve\nChinese banks, whose reserves are based\non silver. With the shrinkage in the\nvalue of these reserves, Chinese banks\nhave been forced to suspend and many\noperators in silver have been ruined.\nThe situation in China has been Inten\nsified by the political disorders espe\ncially those that have grown out of the\nrecent troubles with Russia. The Col\nlapse of the Chinese pool in silver last\nmonth was the result of an overextended\nposition in the metal at a time when\nthe price was rapidly receding.\nIndia is steadily transforming her\ncredit, base from silver to gold, which\nInvolves a constant sale by the govern\nment of silver as the market will ab\nsorb it. It. will be some years yet before\nthis transition period has been com\npleted. The fact that. India must con\ntinue to dispose of silver constitutes a\npermanent weight on the market for the\nmetal, for which there is no counter\nbalance.\nEffect an Mexico.\nAs one of the world\u2019s largest pro\nducers of silver. Mexico has been\nseverely hurt by the slump in the price\nReal Service \u2014Reliably Rendered\nAs you probably have experienced, there are a\n\u201cthousand and one\u201d annoying details continuously\narising in connection with the management of an